{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17601581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17601581"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:16:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:16:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15661"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15661"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.11,0.67,0.04,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8352"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71105"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8352"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15661"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56576"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5884"},{"type":"tags","id":"7004"},{"type":"tags","id":"10110"},{"type":"tags","id":"10124"},{"type":"tags","id":"10592"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20139"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20141"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71105"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents with amenorrhoea and galactorrhoea. MRI reveals a large pituitary mass, and blood tests show markedly elevated prolactin levels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following hormonal changes is most likely to occur due to the elevated prolactin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased thyroid-stimulating hormone levels","Decreased testosterone levels","Low gonadotropin-releasing hormone levels","Increased follicle-stimulating hormone levels","Increased luteinising hormone levels"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn prolactinomas, elevated prolactin leads to suppression of \u003Cstrong\u003Egonadotropin-releasing hormone\u003C/strong\u003E (GnRH) secretion from the hypothalamus. This results in reduced secretion of both \u003Cstrong\u003Eluteinising hormone\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Efollicle-stimulating hormone\u003C/strong\u003E from the anterior pituitary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe reduction in gonadotropins leads to decreased sex hormone production. \u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid-stimulating hormone\u003C/strong\u003E levels are typically unaffected by elevated prolactin. The reduced gonadotropins result in \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased testosterone\u003C/strong\u003E in men and decreased oestrogen in women. This causes symptoms such as amenorrhoea in women and erectile dysfunction in men.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis pattern of low sex hormones and low gonadotropins is known as hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, which is a characteristic feature of prolactinomas.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Elevated prolactin suppresses gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) secretion from the hypothalamus","Prolactinomas cause hypogonadotropic hypogonadism through suppression of GnRH","High prolactin levels lead to decreased oestrogen and testosterone due to reduced gonadotropin secretion"],"references":["Yatavelli RKR, Bhusal K. Prolactinoma. [Updated 2023 Jul 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459347/","Fukuhara N, Nishiyama M, Iwasaki Y. Update in Pathogenesis, Diagnosis, and Therapy of Prolactinoma. Cancers (Basel). 2022 Jul 24;14(15):3604. doi: 10.3390/cancers14153604. PMID: 35892862; PMCID: PMC9331865.","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56576"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15661"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56576"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T23:58:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T23:59:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8352"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71105"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://